My son needed a new bath robe and since we tend to use robes as lounge wear around the house we looked for something comfortable with a little more personality than just a regular terry robe.  We loved the design of this wookie robe, and thought the character matched his own as he is a very tall 7 year-old and likes Star Wars.  It fit just a little more snug than I expected, particularly around his head, but then I had to guess on the sizing.  (More on sizing below.)  But once he tried it on I could not get him to take it off, so we kept it.  It is super soft and comfortable.  It is made of polyester, so its not very absorbent, but it is plush enough that it does absorb a tiny bit.  Previous robes we've had allowed him to just wrap himself in the robe straight out of the bath without a towel.  With this robe we use a towel to dry off first, then put on the robe.  Likewise this will not double as an absorbant cover-up out of the pool.  But it is perfect for before bed or early morning cover up.  It has one large pocket on the right side hip which you can see if you zoom in on the picture.  The design of the bandolier aligns neatly with the belt when tied. The hoodie fits his head for now, but it may get tight on his head before he outgrows the rest of the robe. Overall we love it. If it was a little cheaper we might have thought about getting the Bobba Fett robe for his younger brother.  But for what it is, Star Wars merchandise and good quality of product, we are very satisfied.

Sizing - I am assuming that "Groovy UK" is not an American company, which explains the confusion in sizing.  The robe took 2 weeks to arrive and was shipped in very different packaging than most parcel mail, definitely not shipped from Amazon, but it still arrived ahead of estimated delivery date so we were happy.
The sizing guide is the "Amazon Kids and Baby Size Chart".  It breaks down sizes for Little Boys and Big Boys.  Unfortunately, it does not say whether the seller, "Groovy UK", matches with the Little Boys or the Big Boys sizes. (Or Little/Big Girls for that matter).  Our son's height put him at either a Little Boys large  "L(6)" or a Big Boys small "S(8)".  Our son right now is a 7/8.  The seller only offers sizes medium and large on Amazon, (on the clothing label it just says "kid medium").  I gambled that the sizing would be for Big Boys and ordered the medium, thinking we would get the "M(10-12)".  I thought if it turned out to be too small, then they had used the Little Boys sizing, which would have given us the "M(5)", and we'd send it back for an exchange.  When we got the robe, it fit him comfortably.  It fits him like a size 7, and he is a size 7/8, but that doesn't match up with either of Amazon's sizes of "M".  The only thing I can figure is that the seller's sizes run smaller than Amazon's.  So for "Groovy UK" a medium is not Amazon's "M(10-12)" but more like an 8.  Bottom line, use the Big Kid sizing and order a size up.
summary: Soft & Comfy, Looks Cool, but order a size up

Then I clip the fascinator in, hiding the bobby pins. It looks great, and I've gotten compliments while wearing it.

Be aware, it is large! While it perches more lightly on your hairstyle than a hat-style fascinator would, it will still pretty much dominate your head.

Shipping was good for standard, but I noticed that when I click on "Track your order" through Amazon, it said "returning to sender."  When I checked it on the UPS, I got accurate tracking information that said it was on it's way so I just waited it out.  But I thought it worth mentioning since it sure freaked me out at first.

I just got them today so we'll see how they wear, but they arrived brand new, stitching and eyelets straight.  No obvious pressure points that are going to cause blisters so I'm sure I'll get plenty of wear out of them. Definitely recommend!

reviewText: Excellent product!

It's a nice watch but did not fully meet my expectations. Bought it a month ago.

Design: watch face looks much lighter then I expected. From the pictures it feels that it should be very dark but in reality the top half of the face is very light gray, and the bottom is darker but still much lighter than expected.

Quality: the watch feels very light and fragile. Strap came off, detached from the watch 3 times during the last month, caused by me tightening it too much (wasn't super tight though, it was still wearable with no discomfort at that point). Easy to reattach the strap by hand but doesn't add to the quality feel of the product.

Time keeping: it's very hard to set it more or less precisely. I have to set it up to ~20 min ahead of time for the watch to pick up the correct time. I.e. if it's 2pm then I have to set it to roughly 2.20pm, then it kinda sits there until 2.20pm and then starts showing correct time. And it's hard to figure out the exact offset value.

Date display: the manual says that it comes pre-set for the date to roll-over at midnight. This wasn't my case, it was setup to roll over some time in the afternoon. It's easy to set it correctly but I expected it to work out of the box.

Overall: it's a fine watch overall. I still like to wear it, still looks not bad, and it still shows the time. The time and date setup are documented in the manual so it's not a big deal. But for the price and "german-made" tag I expected more refined product. There are other makes which offer models which feel noticeably better in the same price range.
summary: It's a nice watch but did not fully meet my expectations

reviewText:
I bought this watch because I was intrigued by the 24-hour, single-hand concept and I have to say it is very cool. Despite having less resolution than a typical watch, it's much easier to read once you get used to it and really gives you all the information you actually need. I've only found two downsides to the concept. The first is its usefulness in cooking. Hard to sear a steak for 3 minutes on each side when you can only discern 10 minute increments. The second is that it's pretty difficult to get it set (or even tell it's working) without just waiting for some time to pass. It took me about three days of fiddling with the time before I no longer needed to fine-tune the time on it.

The watch itself is pretty nice. The case is nicely machined and nothing seems loose in the timepiece. VERY light weight. The crown rotates smoothly although there is some hysteresis in its effect. That is, when you change direction of the crown, the hand doesn't reverse direction until it's moved an additional 5-10 minutes (this was a major contributor in my trouble getting it set right). The band, however, could be better. While it looks nice and understated, the material feels cheap and the pins "tick" when the band flexes leading me to believe the pins either don't fit snuggly or will break fairly soon.

Overall, I'm still pretty happy with the watch. Looks nice. Works well. Comfortable.

UPDATE: I had to reduce my rating because this watch is pretty bad at keeping time. It seems to oscillate back and forth around the actual time. As an example, it may be correct at 9:30, but at 11:30 it will read 11: 40 and later at 14:30 it will read 14:20, but by 18:30 it will be reading correct again. The times are just examples though because it doesn't consistently get ahead or behind at predictable intervals. For the first couple of weeks, I had kinda gotten OK with this because if you just leave it alone, it will stay mostly correct. But yesterday, it inexplicable fell behind by about 20 minutes and stayed that way. After resetting it to the correct time, it has been back to "normal" so it doesn't appear to have started running slow (i.e. not a dying battery I don't think).

In general, this thing is just horribly unreliable. So if you want a watch that looks nice, but that you don't intend to take too seriously then this one will work for you. But if you need to be able to trust the time your watch is telling you, you could spend a tenth of the price and get better results.
summary: Good looking, but bad at keeping time

Review for Botta UNO 24 Neo

I will be very neutral and sincere on my review. I will say what I like and what I do not like about this watch and you guys judge if its a worth it.

First of all, it is a $400 plus watch. Which I know could be really expensive for non-watch collector like me. However, there are a few points here that made me consider on buying this watch. Here's a few things I like about the watch :

1) The 24 hours concept : The one and only hand revolves around the watch only once a day. For me it gives me some sort of relaxation on my sense of time. What I mean is that we all are so busy with our lives that somehow we forgot to take things slowly and look at the small things. When I go through my day, this watch kinda tell me to relax and not to rush in doing anything. For me its something that other watch do not have

2) Sappire crystal glass : Extremely durable and scratch resistance. I knocked this watch once at a door knob no sign of scratch found

3) Dress friendly watch : I own several watches and some of them are big and thick. Big and thick watch does not fit under my sleeve. This watch is extremely thin and fit under my sleeve perfectly.

4) Elegant looking : Might sound cliche but this watch is one of a kind. I like the black and green combination more than the white and orange due to sleek and minimal looking.

5) Have a DATE window : I do not buy watch without a date window. Date window is life and it is extremely important!

6) Accurate : This watch use an excellent quartz movement that keep times. I own it more than 3 months now and it does not show any time error for now

However, there are a few things that I think can be better :

1) 3 atm water resistance : Are you serious? For me 3 ATM watch means no water contact watch at all. They say it can withstand light rain and hand wash. I just do not want to take the risk on my $400 watch. Although it is pretty common for a dress watch to have 3ATM water resistance, I would love to this watch to get 5ATM water resistance, at least.

2) Readability : Actually I am okay with the watch readability. But I am writing this to warn folks out there, especially the old ones. It is not that this watch is impossible to read, it just somehow the numbers are a bit small and folks with glass might have a problem reading it. But not me, both my eyes are 10/10

3)

reviewText: When I received this product, I noticed a tiny nick on the side of the case.  I wasn't sure what to make of it, so I photographed it and sent it to the support email.  It was early in the day California time, but late in the day in Germany.  I received a response, directly from the product manager within 30 minutes, who explained that the watches go through multiple levels of quality checks, and occasionally are pulled and inspected to ensure water tightness.  He said that the mark on the side of my case (and it's really tiny) was probably an indication of a watch that had been double checked and the gasket replaced.  He agreed that it was not standard to have a watch go to a consumer with any mar whatsoever.  If I wanted to return it, that would have been fine.  I wore the watch for several days and the tiny nick was just never visible.  I did however get several compliments on the watch right away.  I decided over the course of the week that the nick didn't really matter, and I was encouraged by the quick and proactive response that if I did have a real issue with the watch over time, it would be addressed.  I've kept the watch and happy I did.  I enjoy the whole day view it gives me and find that it's a perfect example of a case where analog trumps digital, as it provides so much more information and context than a digital readout ever could.  This is an awesome watch from a company that cares about its customers. I've attached a photo so you can see what I was talking about.  Does not stop me from highly recommending the watch.
summary: Great watch from a company that cares.

In a few words I can honestly say that I love these boots. They are very unique and a very specific style that I spent several weeks looking for. I can say that I am very glad that I found these because they are pretty much exactly what I was looking for.

As for the quality, I have owned several pairs of Demonia boots and I have worn every one of them until there was nothing left to wear. I literally walked out the front of one pair and out the back of another, not because of build quality but because I spent 2 or 3 years wearing each pair until they just fell apart.
As far as these boots go, the quality is just what I expected from Demonia. They walk well and after the first few days of getting used to them I find them very comfortable. My only real complaint is the "man-made leather" that Demonia loves to use on any of their boots that cost under $200. If these were real leather I'd have no complaints at all. An option for plain, non-skull buckles would have been nice too but since they are covered by my pants I can live with them.

So basicly if you are looking for some unique brogue style shoes but prefer boots like me, these are great and you really can't beat the price either.

reviewText:
I write this review with tremendous conflict.

I used to look at (photoshopped) pictures of men modeling shirts thinking "Of course I can make my shirt look like that the moment I tuck it in at home, but the moment I sit in my car to go anywhere, it is going to come partially untucked and 'blouse' out at the bottom. I don't want to have to excuse myself to a restroom or do the shirt tuck dance every time I stand up from a seated position, nor do I want to remain standing at all times just to have my shirt look nice." Then my friend told me of what he called shirt stays (which is what I'm going to call them for this review because "Holdup ShirtTail Tightning Straps called Stay Downs in Y-style with Composite Plastic Gripper Clasps" is too wordy), and described this product. I eventually placed my order.

The package came unceremoniously in a plastic bag packaging, complete with a suspenders catalogue for all your suspender needs. Nothing wrong with this, it just made me chuckle. I observed the unique clamps which I hadn't expected to work the way they did. Again, not a bad thing, just not what I expected. And the stretchy material used to put it all together. I noticed near the sock-end of the contraption what I thought was velcro, but upon an attempted tug thought it must be sewn.

The following morning, I get dressed. Starting like I normally would, I put on my underwear first. Followed by my socks, then undershirt. I put on my dress shirt, button it up, and decide this is the moment to dawn my new shirt stays. Letting gravity work with me, I attach them to the bottom of my shirt first, and immediately realize they're too long. The bottom clasps are hanging well below the tops of my socks. I'm a bit smaller than average (5'7" tall with a 30 inch inseam), but these are hanging inches too low. I look carefully at the package again along with the shirt stays and realize the velcro I noticed from the day before is NOT sewn down, and pull hard enough I thought something might break. I "adjust" them to the smallest setting, and manage to connect them to my socks without having them snap back and break out my teeth. Proud of my work, I stand tall, feeling the slight tug from my socks to the tops of my shoulders (without pants yet), and decide these things are great! I put on my pants, and shoes and realize that anyone who decides to take a peek is clearly going to see odd bulges and bumps where the clasps are under the pants. I push the voice inside my head to the side, insisting that the voice is being paranoid and go to work.

The strap along the sides of my legs becomes less noticeable in short order, but the clasps are harder to ignore. After a few hours of work, and a few cups of coffee it is time to use the restroom, and that's when it hits the fan.

I step into the stall to take my morning deuce, and pull at the bottom of my shirt to untuck it from my pants like I always do, and it isn't moving. "Of course it isn't because it's attached to your socks numb-nuts." I think to myself. "So what? Maybe not everyone untucks their shirts first, just pull down your pants." This is when it all begins to occur to me what nightmare I just woke up in. I can't pull down my underwear with my pants because my shirt is still tucked in. So I try to pull down just my pants and bend back my thumbnail that gets caught on the darn clasp. Once again, I try to pull up my shirt in order to get to the top of my underwear, but it still isn't budging because like before, it is attached to my socks. I contort my wrists to pull down my underwear by the leg holes, and start to assume the position, only to realize the shirt stays are pulling the bottom of my shirt to cover my hiney, and if I'm not super mindful of this, I'm going to poo on my shirt tail.

I manage to.... ahem.... clear the area, do what I need to do and take care of my business. Afterwards, glad to still have a clean shirt, I stand up off the toilet, grab my underwear and pants to pull them up, together, in one motion, as I have done for over 30 years, only to get them to the tops of my thighs before I am once again encumbered by the bottom of my shirt, which is still attached to my socks by the shirt stays. I let go, and my belt buckle pulls my pants back to the ground with a loud clank, leaving my underwear at the top of my thighs, and my hands empty as I can't believe I have to give this much thought on how to get re-dressed. I bend over at the waist, attempting to bring my elbows to my knees in order to get my hands a better angle to grab the top of my underwear and try to drag it up into position. Once the underwear was back into position, pulling up the pants was easy, and the shirt stays meant I didn't have to put for any effort whatsoever to tuck my shirt in.

However, by the third go round of this in the day (fortunately, I'm very regular), the clasps decided they simply couldn't take it anymore, and came undone as I pulled up my pants (or down, I can't even remember now), and just didn't have the staying power it started with in the morning.

Do they do what they're supposed to do? Yes. And really, that's important, maybe the most important. It isn't that these are bad quality, or don't work, because the fact is they do work. However, are they practical? Not really, especially for people who wear underwear, and use the bathroom. They would be far less cumbersome if you're going commando. They also wouldn't be so bad if you were only going to wear them over a short enough period of time that you wouldn't be going to use a toilet in that time frame. But trying to wear them all day, with underwear, and multiple trips to the toilet is asking a lot. And if you have some kind of GI problem such as Crohn's disease, or IBS, then you're playing with fire.

I'm never wearing them again. And I couldn't recommend them to anyone without telling them this story so they aren't blindsided in a restroom, having to think through a situation that should just be second nature.
summary: Useful if you don't wear underwear or use the bathroom.

I love these shoes for little ones because it allows their feet to grow naturally, without constricting them like regular shoes.  It is very important early on in a child's life to allow their foot to grow naturally, because shoes will "shape" a child's foot, often to unhealthy positions early on while they are learning to walk.  These little sock shoes allow for the child's foot to form naturally and grow with the sock, rather than be confined within a shoe and restricting growth.  I always buy these for my children.

My only complaint is that 24 months is the biggest size they have.  I wish I could purchase them until Kindergarten!  My child's foot will continue to grow and form for years, but after this I have to move on to regular constricting shoes.

For years, I've suffered through the issues around jeans and fitted shirts. I had to choose the lesser of two evils - either have my pants held up securely or have a nice, neat, flat front profile to my pants. Too many times, I had to choose the secure keeping-on of the pants and tolerate a bulging belt buckle. Now that I've purchased this belt, I can have BOTH of the things I've so long sought. I wear this belt ALL the time. It's awesome and appears to quite flexible relative to waist size.
summary: This is the belt I've been looking for FOREVER!

reviewText:
My husband has been hasseling me for years to wear a belt, but I have always hated the bulk the buckle added to my waistband. I finally decided to search on Amazon for a flat buckle belt. This was the only option that actually looked stylish.

I'm really pleased with this belt. The elastic is very strong, it is easy to adjust, and it looks great.

Sure, this is one of the most expensive belts in this category, but it's price matches that of its quality. It stretched just enough to stay comfortable, while keeping everything on. The clasp is nice and high quality, and its all virtually invisible under my shirt.

I will update this review after a few months of wearing it to test durability, but at the moment, it's very nice.

I love this belt.  It lays flat and unnoticible under my shirts.  What's additionally awesome is I forget I'm wearing a belt because it stays in place and doesn't ride up and hit my tummy when bending over.  The metal buckle is sturdy, easy to use and very durable.  The belt material lays flat and fits my belt loops on my hiking pants perfect.
Very nice belt, comfortable, stylish. Flat buckle is easy to close and open. Adjustable length for waist and hips. . Have worn it every day since receiving it. Really love it.

I have worn this belt at least two dozen times since I purchased it.  I initially bought it to use with two pairs of jeans that I own where the zipper gapped open creating a bulky look underneath shirts.  The belt took care of that.  I now also use it for pants where the waist gaps in the back.  I like the metal buckle because it looks so much nicer than plastic for when I tuck a shirt into my pants.  I like this belt so much that I just ordered two more in different colors even though I think that the price is way too high.  On the other hand, I have bought belts that cost more and those are hanging in the closet unworn.  As other reviewers mentioned, swapping out the belt among pants takes a little bit of effort as does fitting the buckle through the loops but otherwise this belt does exactly what I wanted it to do.

I was previously (shamefully) using baseball belts to avoid "the bulge" of a regular belt, but decided it was time to get something much more stylish.  I love the look AND how flat this belt lays!  I keep asking myself why I waited so long to purchase this...
summary: Exactly what I was looking for!

Although it does look weird, it is more comfortable than my old 'horseshoe' neck pillow. As others have commented, it is smaller than I expected. Apparently, the non-inflatable one is a bit larger, which is even more puzzling when you consider that the inflatable one -- unconstrained by storage size limitations when deflated -- could actually be far larger when inflated.

The other minor annoyance is that the inflation nipple lacks an internal 'check' valve common on other inflatable items. This means that you have to very quickly shut the stopper after adding air or else it will be too soft. I'd like to believe that they explicitly decided to NOT include such a valve in order to prevent bursting when cabin pressure decreases during ascent. That would be an impressive amount of analysis and forethought...but it seems unlikely.
summary: Looks weird and is a bit too small, but comfortable

reviewText: I will be ordering another! I left mine on my last plane home  it was an excellent travel companion. I traveled for five weeks in just a backpack, and I loved how little space it took up. I had to get used to inflating it. The first few tries felt like I was making out with it, but it got easier. I lived the softness of the cover. It was very nice. You can inflate a lot for a firmer pillow, or deflate for something squishier. It made cramped sleeping spots on trains, boats, and planes more comfortable.

And while the original J-pillow is pretty comfortable to the both of us, we found the inflatable version to be far less so in that regard. It simply is too small to fit as comfortably around our big noggins. My mother however found it to be just perfect for her but she is a petite little thing by comparison to us.

So if you're a fairly tall and heavy set person, I can't recommend this product in good conscience when compared to the original version. That said, its inflatable nature means that it will always have a home in my travel tote, but nowhere else.

reviewText:
Some people sleep on their sides with a bent neck, some others must have their neck aligned straight to be comfortable.  This is all dependent on your persona preference.  Most people, physiologically and biologically speaking, will feel more comfortable when their vertebra is properly alined and not bent.  That's why so many pillows are uncomfortable (talking about bed pillows at home) because your vertebra is not aligned.  Your cervical spine section is crooked comparing to the rest of the lumbar sections of your spine.  So, having said that...

This pillow makes you sleep side ways.  Unless that is totally you, this pillow will cause your neck to be bent in an angle not different than sleeping on a bad pillow.  It is bad.  Or I should say, it should be bad for most people, physiologically speaking.  You might  be different though.

My recommendation is to NOT go with it.  I tried it for several times and it is just not comfortable.  A great idea though!  Good thoughtful design behind it.  But your neck is still crooked which means discomfort.

Hope this helps!
summary: A thoughtful physiological review to help you decide.  Hope it works for you!  It doesn't for me and several friends here..

reviewText: I am not a DJ. I fancy myself as an audiophile. I have a large 45rpm collection. I thought this stabilizer/weight would be just what I was looking for. I have issues with warped records, more so with vinyl records. This seems to be a much less problem withs styrene. I would like to elliminate as much of the "warp wobble" as possible when playing a record. The sabilizier does a very nice job of this. Even records with larger warps, it can still help eliminate much of it. I have posted a video of a 45 with a slight/medium warp. The stabilizer also helps with records that are bowed in the center, where the center is much higher than the outer edge of the record. This causes an angle/slant to the record that would effect play. Once you place the stabilizer on the record, it would flatten the record, or as near to flat as it can get. Even if the record was bowed the other way, it would still flatten the outer edge of the record even if it was only slight. I really like the stabilizer and it does a great job. I thought by the description it would not be heavy enough but now that I have it I can tell you it is plenty heavy enough to do the job is was designed for, I gave it 4 out of 5 stars because I thought it was kinda pricey. But, I would recommend this to anyway.
summary: Excellent product.  Works as it should.  Any serious collector should have one!

reviewText: Very good wig, good color ! But, no, it's not perfect :/

First, the positive:
1. Came a LOT earlier than expected. I think maybe a week? Two?

3. It looks great for a ponytail wig. I was hesitant on buying a ponytail wig because sometimes they don't look the best but I'm pretty happy with how it looks. It also has a really nice color which I think is pretty close to Hanji's hair color.
Now for the negative:
1. It looks nice on the top layer, but the layer underneath was frizzy. I can fix it, but it's very noticeable after brushing it.
2. Like one of the other reviewers said, the ponytail was a bit messy. I'm sure with some time, patience, and wig styling, it'll look better. It also could be from the packaging.
3. It was tighter than I liked it to be. Hopefully with time as I continue to wear it, it'll stretch out a bit, but it gives me a headache wearing it.

Overall, I think it's a pretty nice wig since the negatives are mainly things I can fix.

After leaving a review for something else my Amazon popped up that I never reviewed this - and I couldn't understand why because I use it daily! I looked on the page and saw a couple of negative reviews that it was falling apart so I figured I'd leave my feedback:

I am NOT NICE to my things. I'm terrible. My purse has like 500 things in it - umbrella, deodorant, hairbrush, wallet, checkbook, hat and gloves, etc. etc. you get the point. And it's not necessarily a "large" purse, pretty medium sized. And I shove things into it that shouldn't fit all the time, like a pair of heels to change into, on top of everything else already in there. So I was surprised to see people saying their case was falling apart! Because it survives being one of my 24/7 purse items, crammed around with everything else. I even brought this case backpacking through Norway and it survived! I mean maybe the other ones were just defects? But I use this often, and I shove it into terrible places and shove things on top of it, and my raybans have yet to break (*knock on wood*). I bring it almost daily to Central park in a beach bag as well, so lots of opening and closing and good usage! It actually looks and functions like it was still brand new.

For reference they fit aviators but I do not think they would fit the wayfarers. I haven't tried though, I gave my wayfarers to my sister because they are too big for my face.
